<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-03-09T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-03-09T19:00:00-05:00" n="346" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d346">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">693.001/521: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-03-09T19:00:00-05:00">March 9,
                                    1939—7 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>54. Your 123, March 8, 4 p.m., trade restrictions in North China. The
                            Department is inclined to agree with your view but raises for your
                            consideration the question whether or not the reasons in favor of an
                            informal approach are outweighed by the desirability of going along with
                            the British wherever practicable in cases where no conflict of principle
                            is involved. The Department desires that you exercise your discretion in
                            the matter.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>